# NestJS Clean Code & TDD Standards

## Priority Legend
- 🔴 **Critical** - Must follow, no exceptions
- 🟠 **High** - Strong recommendation, deviate only with good reason
- 🟡 **Standard** - Expected practice
- 🟢 **Recommended** - Best practice but flexible

---

## Project Setup & Architecture

- 🔴 **Follow NestJS standard module structure** with controllers, services, and providers
- 🟠 **Use dependency injection** for all services and external dependencies
- 🟡 **Organize code by domain/feature** rather than technical layer (e.g., `users/`, `orders/`)
- 🔴 **Never import from implementation details** - Always use public API (index.ts/public-api.ts)
- 🟠 **Keep modules focused and cohesive** - One responsibility per module
- 🟡 **Use NestJS decorators properly** (`@Module`, `@Injectable`, `@Controller`, etc.)

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Feature-based module structure
src/
├── users/
│   ├── users.module.ts
│   ├── users.controller.ts
│   ├── users.service.ts
│   ├── users.repository.ts
│   ├── dto/
│   │   ├── create-user.dto.ts
│   │   └── update-user.dto.ts
│   ├── entities/
│   │   └── user.entity.ts
│   └── tests/
│       ├── users.service.spec.ts
│       ├── users.controller.spec.ts
│       └── users.repository.spec.ts
│
├── orders/
│   └── ...
│
├── shared/
│   ├── decorators/
│   ├── filters/
│   ├── interceptors/
│   ├── guards/
│   ├── pipes/
│   └── ...

// ❌ BAD: Technical layer-based structure
src/
├── controllers/
├── services/
├── repositories/
├── dto/
└── entities/
```

---

## Controllers & Routing

- 🔴 **Keep controllers thin** - Only handle HTTP concerns, delegate business logic to services
- 🟠 **Use proper HTTP methods** (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH) for CRUD operations
- 🔴 **Validate all inputs** using class-validator and DTOs with decorators
- 🟠 **Implement consistent error handling** with proper HTTP status codes
- 🟡 **Use path parameters wisely** - Keep routes clean and semantic
- 🔴 **Never access database directly** from controllers - Always use services

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Thin controller with validation
@Controller('users')
@ApiTags('users')
export class UsersController {
  constructor(private readonly usersService: UsersService) {}

  @Post()
  @ApiOperation({ summary: 'Create a new user' })
  async create(@Body() createUserDto: CreateUserDto): Promise<UserResponse> {
    return this.usersService.create(createUserDto);
  }

  @Get(':id')
  @ApiOperation({ summary: 'Get user by ID' })
  async findOne(@Param('id', ParseIntPipe) id: number): Promise<UserResponse> {
    const user = await this.usersService.findById(id);
    if (!user) {
      throw new NotFoundException(`User with ID ${id} not found`);
    }
    return user;
  }

  @Put(':id')
  @ApiOperation({ summary: 'Update user' })
  async update(
    @Param('id', ParseIntPipe) id: number,
    @Body() updateUserDto: UpdateUserDto
  ): Promise<UserResponse> {
    return this.usersService.update(id, updateUserDto);
  }

  @Delete(':id')
  @ApiOperation({ summary: 'Delete user' })
  async remove(@Param('id', ParseIntPipe) id: number): Promise<void> {
    await this.usersService.remove(id);
  }
}

// ❌ BAD: Fat controller with business logic
@Controller('users')
export class UsersController {
  constructor(private db: Database) {}

  @Post()
  async create(@Body() body: any) {
    // Business logic mixed with HTTP logic
    const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(body.password, 10);
    const user = await this.db.users.create({
      email: body.email,
      password: hashedPassword,
      // ... more logic
    });
    return user;
  }
}
```

