## Clean Code Principles for NestJS

- 🔴 **Avoid nested if statements** - Use guard clauses and early returns
- 🔴 **Limit function parameters** - Max 2-3, use object destructuring for more
- 🔴 **Keep methods small** - Under 50 lines of code
- 🔴 **Single Responsibility Principle** - Each class/method does one thing
- 🟠 **Use meaningful names** - Variables, functions, and classes should reveal intent
- 🟠 **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)** - Extract common logic into helper functions
- 🟡 **Use early return pattern** - Reduce nesting and improve readability
- 🟡 **Group related functionality** - Keep cohesive code together
- 🟠 **Minimize comments** - Write self-documenting code
- 🟡 **YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It)** - Don't add features preemptively
- 🟡 **Fail fast** - Detect and report errors early

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Clean code with early returns
async createUser(createUserDto: CreateUserDto): Promise<User> {
  const existingUser = await this.usersRepository.findByEmail(
    createUserDto.email
  );
  
  if (existingUser) {
    throw new BadRequestException('Email already in use');
  }

  const hashedPassword = await this.passwordService.hash(
    createUserDto.password
  );

  return this.usersRepository.create({
    ...createUserDto,
    password: hashedPassword
  });
}

// ❌ BAD: Nested conditionals and unclear logic
async createUser(body: any) {
  if (body.email) {
    const existing = await this.db.users.findOne({ email: body.email });
    if (!existing) {
      if (body.password) {
        const hash = await bcrypt.hash(body.password, 10);
        if (hash) {
          const user = await this.db.users.create({
            email: body.email,
            password: hash,
            name: body.name
          });
          if (user) {
            return user;
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

